Referrin'g to this massacre of helpless fugitives, Plutarch, in his ‘⁴ Life of Caesar,” writes that when the Senate was voting public thanksgiving and processions on account of the victory, Cato proposed that Caesar should be given up to the barbarians to expiate that breach of saith, in order that the divine vengeance might fall upon its author rather than upon Rome. Cato was Caesar’s bitter political and personal enemy, but still Caesar’s cruelty and perfidy in this transaction can be justified only on the ground of absolute necessity. To secure the Roman power, he must destroy these Germans in order to establish the Rhine as the Gallie frontier and deter others from crossing.
